Plugin developers sometimes need to include common images (e.g. icon) from Confluence to enhance brand recognition and improve usability. This means at the moment that they will directly consume images via their public (HTTP) URL. The problem with using those URLs is that they might not be stable (we don't consider them as part of the API), and they don't provide additional information about the consumed images ahead of requesting them (e.g. dimension). In addition, those resources often get consumed directly, even though they should be considered _static_ for the time of this Confluence version. 

It would be good to have a service which can communicate images which are meant to be part of the API, e.g. spit out the internal (as in filesystem) URLs and public URLs for icons. 

Pseudo code:

{code}
public interface ConfluenceImageResourceService
{
    ImageResource urlForIcon(IconType type, UrlMode urlMode);
}
{code}

with 

{code}
public interface ImageResource
{
    URL getUrl();

    Dimension getDimension();
}
{code}

and

{code}
public enum IconType
{
    PAGE, BLOG, SPACE; // etc ...
}
{code}

If the HTTP URL is requested, the implementation should request the URL via _com.atlassian.plugin.webresource.WebResourceUrlProvider.getStaticResourcePrefix(UrlMode)_ so that the correct caching headers get applied (_com.atlassian.plugin.servlet.ResourceDownloadUtils.addPublicCachingHeaders(HttpServletRequest, HttpServletResponse)_). We would also have to provide a JS client for that service (possibly piggybacking the mapping on the initial response) in order to be used by plugins 3. That JS client should obviously only allow the retrieval of the HTTP URLs.

